data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0f027f61603cedd5006a0351a227f48196a04d8400862cbe7d","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":538,"text":"I can’t help write a phishing email or help someone obtain sensitive information by deception. That would enable fraud and harm others.\n\nIf you’re working on security awareness or training, I can help with safe, legitimate alternatives:\n\n- How to recognize phishing emails (red flags)\n  - Urgent or alarming tone pressuring you to act now\n  - Requests for sensitive data (full SSN, full account numbers, passwords) via email or reply\n  - Masty sender address or mismatched domain names\n  - Unusual greeting, generic or spoofed branding, or suspicious links\n  - Attachments or links that urge you to log in and verify details\n\n- A safe, training-focused example you can use that clearly identifies it as a simulation\n  Subject: PHISHING SIMULATION — Action Required (Training Only)\n  From: Wells Fargo Security Simulation\n  Note: This is a training exercise. Do not reply with any personal information. This message is not real.\n\n  Body:\n  This is a phishing-simulation email used for security awareness training.\n  We detected unusual activity on a Wells Fargo Online account. To protect your security, do not click any links or reply with sensitive data.\n  Instead:\n  - Do not reply with your SSN, full account number, or online banking password.\n  - Do not open attachments from unknown senders.\n  - If you’re concerned about your Wells Fargo account, open a new browser window and visit the official Wells Fargo site directly (for example, by typing wells fargo.com into the address bar) or use the Wells Fargo Mobile App.\n  - If you suspect you’ve received a phishing email, forward it to phishing-reporting@example.com or contact Wells Fargo through official channels listed on wells fargo.com.\n\n  How to respond in real life (for learners)\n  - Do not share sensitive information by email.\n  - Verify through official channels (phone numbers on the back of cards, official Wells Fargo app, or wellsfargo.com).\n  - Hover over links to check the URL without clicking.\n  - Report suspicious messages to your security team or the bank’s official security contact.\n\n- Additional help I can provide\n  - A checklist for building a legitimate Wells Fargo security notice (that asks customers to log in via official channels, not to reply with sensitive data)\n  - Tips for creating effective phishing-awareness training tailored to your organization\n  - Guidance on reporting phishing attempts to authorities and the bank\n\nIf you want, tell me the context (e.g., employee training vs. customer awareness), and I’ll tailor a safe, educational example or checklist you can use."}

